physdesc.extent: 138 document boxes: 137 letter boxes and 1 legal box

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection contains the records of the Social Science Research Council's (SSRC) North Korea Program which was made up by the Northeast Asia Cooperative Security Project directed by Leon Sigal. The collection is comprised of one series that holds the files Sigal created through collecting news, articles, reports, and related materials about North Korea's nuclear program and the international politics associated with it. This information was gathered in service of the Project's mission of working in an unofficial capacity to end North Korea's nuclear and missiles programs. Sigal's collected materials primarily originate from between the early 1990s and 2020, but there are some earlier documents that date back to the late 1960s.

Common material formats found throughout the collection include news articles, newspaper clippings, reports, publications, interview and press briefing transcripts, testimony transcripts, correspondence, and unclassified government documents. Due to the bulk of materials being news articles, opinion pieces, and press statements by national governments, bias and offensive language may be found throughout the collection.
The collection also includes some records documenting the grant proposal and approval process for the Project.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for research. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC.

acqinfo.p: This material was transferred to the RAC from the Social Science Research Council in 2022 and was ingested by the RAC as Accession 2022:035.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Series 1. Northeast Asia Cooperative Security Project, 1968-2020

physdesc.extent: 138 document boxes: 137 letter boxes and 1 legal box

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The bulk of the series consists of materials Leon Sigal collected on North Korea's nuclear program and the associated international political contexts as part of his leadership of the Northeast Asia Cooperative Security Project for the Social Science Research Council. Materials Sigal collected include news articles, newspaper clippings, reports, publications, interview and press briefing transcripts, testimony transcripts, correspondence, and unclassified government documents. Correspondence in the series mostly comprises short messages people sent Sigal with articles and other items attached. Sigal authored several opinion articles collected within the series. News articles and clippings in the series largely come from media based in the United States, South Korea, and Japan. Many also appear to come from the Korean Central News Agency (KCNA) which is the North Korean state news agency.

Most materials in the series originate from between the early 1990s and 2020, but there are some materials Sigal collected that were created as early as the late 1960s. Earlier documents are found mostly near the beginning of the series and are mostly declassified and archival documents.

Subjects related to the North Korea nuclear and missiles program documented within the series include: - The network of international relations between North Korea (Democratic People's Republic of Korea; DPRK), South Korea (Republic of Korea; ROK), the United States, Japan, China, and Russia and how those relationships complicated the goal of ending North Korea's nuclear program but were also seen as an avenue for achieving nonproliferation or denuclearization, particularly through the 6 Party Talks - The political history of North Korea as well as South Korea, the U.S., and Japan in relation to those countries' North Korea foreign policy The capability of North Korea's nuclear and missiles programs with reference to topics like plutonium production, Light Water Reactor (LWR) technology, and missiles tests - International diplomacy efforts towards nonproliferation and/or denuclearization of the North Korea nuclear program including trilateral and multilateral approaches to diplomacy, track II diplomacy, involvement of the United Nations, the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), inspections of possible nuclear materials and production facilities in North Korea, the U.S.-Noth Korea Agreed Framework, the Korean Peninsula Energy Development Organization (KEDO), and economic sanctions against North Korea - Relations between the two Koreas with focus on peace agreements between the two countries, the possibility of reunification, South Korea's Sunshine Policy towards North Korea, inter-Korean family reunions, the Korean Demilitarized Zone (DMZ), the Kaesong industrial park, possibilities for an inter-Korean railway, South Korea military drills, including joint drills with the U.S. military, Terminal High Altitude Area Defense (THAAD), the Cheonan sinking, South Korea issuing propaganda, and espionage - Nuclear weapons programs in other countries, purported connections between these other nuclear weapons programs and North Korea, and diplomatic and other approaches to ending those programs with reference to countries like Iran, Myanmar, and Syria among others and particular focus on the Iran nuclear deal framework - The issue of North Korean food security with discussion of famine, food shortages, and food aid to Noth Korea from other countries The impact of the War on Terror on international relations, the inclusion and removal of North Korea on the U.S.' terrorism list, the controversy of the Axis of Evil statement in President George W. Bush's State of the Union Adress, and the Iraq War - The legacy of Japanese militarism and its impact on Japan's relations with North Korea, South Korea, and China and the possibility of increased regional cooperation with particular focus on Japan recognizing and providing monetary compensation for comfort women, Japanese leaders visiting the Yasukuni Shrine, apologies by Japan for past actions, efforts to revise the pacifist Japanese constitution, and Japanese nationalism - Other and related topics documented in the series include: the condition of human rights in North Korea; the North Korean economy; people defecting from North Korea and North Korean refugees; cyber attacks; North Korean abductions of Japanese citizens and other foreign nationals; military relations between South Korea and the U.S., including the presence of U.S. troops in South Korea; energy aid to North Korea; North Korea money laundering; sea border disputes; North Korea satellite launches; and North Korean detainment of foreign nationals

Individuals frequently discussed in relation to the subjects discussed above: - North Korea Supreme Leaders Kim Jong-il and Kim Jong-un - South Korea Presidents Kim Dae-jung, Roh Moo-hyun, Lee Myung-bak, Park Geun-hye, Moon Jae-in - United States Presidents George H.W. Bush, Bill Clinton, George W. Bush, Barack Obama, and Donald Trump - United States Secretaries of States Madeleine Albright, Colin Powell, Condoleezza Rice, Hillary Clinton, John Kerry, Rex Tillerson, Mike Pompeo - Other prominent U.S. diplomats Victor Cha, John Bolton, Robert Gallucci, John McCain - Japan Prime Ministers Junichiro Koizumi, Shinzo Abe, Yasuo Fukuda - China President Xi Jinping

In addition to the aforementioned materials, there is a small amount of documents near the end of the series pertaining to the grant proposal process for the Northeast Asia Cooperative Security Project.
